Students who did not attend the statistics course exam have been excluded from the data. The data contains 166 participants with the female-male ratio of 2:1 and the age range of 1755. The four variables attitude, deep,stra and surf have been formed on the scale 15, and are somewhat normally distributed with no apparent gender differences based on visual inspection. Between these four variables there is no remarkable correlation except for surf and deep in the case of men (cor = -0.622). On the contrary, for women there is no correlation between these two variables (cor = -0.087). The points variable depicting the points from the course exams gets values from 7 to 33. It is moderately correlated with attitude (cor= 0.4 for females, cor = 0.5 for men) but not with the other variables.

Based on our final model with every unit increase for attitude point are increased by 3 units on average. The Multiple R-squared of the model is 0.19, meaning that 19% of the variance of points is explained by this model, i.e. attitude.

plot(m,which=c(1,2,5))

The assumption of the linear regression model are that the dependent variable is normally distributed and that the residuals are normally distributed, and independent of each other as well as of the values of the variables in the model. Based on the pairwise plot displayed in the beginning of this exercise (Chapt. 2) and the distribution shown in the very right bottom corner of it, points is somewhat normally distributed. The assumptions related to the residuals of the model also seem to hold quite nicely: they seem to be randomly distributed around zero independent of the fitted values (Residuals vs Fitted plot), normally distributed (Quantile-quantile plot) and no specific datapoints e.g.outliers are having too much of an influence on the model as the leverage is very small (max=0.05 based on Residuals vs.Leverage).

High/ low alcohol consumption

To investigate factors associated with high/ low alcohol consumption I chose the following four variables:

  1. sex (binary: F - female or M - male)
  2. address (binary: U - urban or R - rural)
  3. weekly studytime (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)
  4. mothers job (nominal: teacher, health care related, civil services (e.g.administrative or police), at_home or other)

I chose these variables as a wanted to have a mixture of binary, ordinal and categorical variables and I felt like these variables might well be associated with alcohol use.

Preliminary Hypotheses

My hypothesis (based on previous knowledge and intuition) is that men will be more prone to high consumption than women, students from rural areas will be more prone to high consumption, study time will be negatively correlated (i.e.the more you study the more likely you are to be a low consumer of alcohol), and that there will not be great differences between students with mothers working in different job categories. The minor differences for this last variable might be such that those with mothers working for civil services or belonging to category other will be more likely to be high consumers of alcohol than those with mothers working as teachers, in the health care or at home.

Variable distributions and general assessment of variable relations with alcohol consumption

Based on the below summary statistics and the barplots of the individual variables seen on the diagonal of the pairwise plot(Figure 2), luckily the magority of the students do not fall under the category high consumers of alcohol. High consumers of alcohol only constitute 30% of the data. The sex ratio is almost 1:1, with females taking the lead. Only less than 1/4 of the students live in the rural areas as opposed to the urban areas. The category Other is the most popular answer for mothers job, services being the second most common and health the least. Studytime per week has been categorized into 4 ordinal groups the two lowest categories getting most of the values.

Paying attention to the blue and red colours representing high and low consumption of alcohol respectively in the Figure 2, we note from the diagonal plots that address, sex and studytime, seem to be associated with consumption status. Based on the boxplots (better boxplots lower down, Figure 3) studytime seems to be clearly associated with alcohol consumption: High consumers spend less time studying per week than non-high users. This pattern can be seen irrespective of address and mainly mothers job. Nevertheless, for men this pattern does not apply as they seem to study less than women as a whole, irrespective of their alcohol consumption.

These associations are in line with my original hypotheses.

Logistic regression

Based on the summary of the logistic regression below, only sex and studytime are statistically significantly (p<0.05) associated with high alcohol consumption. Looking at the confidence intervals of the odds ratios related to those variables that are not statistically significant in the model, we note that 1 is included in the interval. Sex has an OR of 1.9 for men, meaning that men have twice as high odds of being a high consumer of alcohol compared to women. Studytime, the only other statistically significant explanatory variable, has an OR of 0.6, meaning that at every unit increase in studytime, the odds of being a high consumer is nearly halved from the previous studytime unit.

#logistic regression
m <- glm(high_use ~ sex + address + Mjob + studytime, data = alc, family = "binomial")

Predictive power of the finalized logistic regression model

Next using, the variables that had a statistically significant relationship with alcohol consumption, I will explore the predictive power of my model.

####
#logistic regression
m2 <- glm(high_use ~ sex + studytime, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# predict() the probability of high_use
alc$high_use_prob<- predict(m2, type = "response")

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc$high_use_pred <- alc$high_use_prob > 0.5

# see the last ten original classes, predicted probabilities, and class predictions
tail(alc[,c("high_use", "high_use_prob", "high_use_pred")])

Our model ends up categorizing all individuals as non-high consumers of alcohol. I will next do the same including absences in the model.

m3 <- glm(high_use ~ sex + studytime + absences , data = alc, family = "binomial")

# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$high_use_pred) #proportion of wrongly predicted values.
## [1] 0.2565445
(10+88)/382 #We get the same anwer when calculating the off diagonal values from the previous table over all values.
## [1] 0.2565445
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = 0) #comparing to simply guessing none are high users. This gives worse results than the model with absences!
## [1] 0.2984293

Bsed on the model including absences we actually get a lot better predictions and do not systematically end putting everyone in to the FALSE category. This model ends up falsely classifying a quarter of the data, whereas our previous model (or a directly classifying all in to the FALSE category) would end up falsely classifying one third of the students.

Chapter 4: Clustering and classification

Key words: k-means clustering, Euclidean distance, Manhattan distnace, standardizing, centering, scaling, linear discriminant analysis, preicting classes (training and test sets), within sum of squares

Boston data set

Introduction

The Boston data set can be loaded from the MASS R-package. The data is described here. It contains infromation such as per capita crime rate by town and pupil-teacher ratio by town for the suburbs of Boston. The data frame has 506 rows (towns) and 14 columns (variables). All variables are numeric except for rad(=index of accessibility to radial highways) and chas(=Charles River dummy variable: 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise) which are coded as integer variables by default. Based on summary statistics and histograms (lower) we note that all are continuous variables, except that rad is ordinal and chas a dummy variable.

Data preparation for cluster analysis

Scaling

In cluster analysis we are interested in the distances between observations as we want to see which observations are closer to each other than the others. In order to calculate comparable distances, we need to ensure all variables are on the same scale. Hence, I scaled all the variables after which they all had a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one (see below, second summary table). Nevertheless, looking at the minimum, maximum and quartiles, it is indisputable that the variables are still very skewed (the two summary outputs below), infact their distribution plots are exactly the same as well as their pairwise correlations which can be seen from Figure 3: only the scale of the variable changes. Linear discriminant analysis, which we will soon use, actually assumes all variables to be normally distributed. So if we were to do the analysis properly we could for example rank transform the variables to normality, but we will not do this now as we will stick to the instructions of the exercise.

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

K-means clustering

K-means clustering is the oldest most commonly used clustering method as it often finds a solution as is easy to use. Nevertheless, it isnt very robust: any changes in the dataset may result in different solutions.

Distances between observations

We calculate the euclidian and manhattan distances between the observations. We note that their ranges are very different.

Optimal number of clusters via K-means clustering

We continue with the commonly used euclidian distances to complete k-means clustering. First starting off with four clusters we note from the pairwise scatterplot which is coloured based on cluster, that the green and red clusters are perhaps the most important clusters regarding the majority of the variables.

# k-means clustering
km4 <-kmeans(dist_eu, centers = 4)
summary(km4)
##              Length Class  Mode   
## cluster       506   -none- numeric
## centers      2024   -none- numeric
## totss           1   -none- numeric
## withinss        4   -none- numeric
## tot.withinss    1   -none- numeric
## betweenss       1   -none- numeric
## size            4   -none- numeric
## iter            1   -none- numeric
## ifault          1   -none- numeric
# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston_scaled, col = km4$cluster)

# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 20

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(dist_eu, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
plot(1:k_max, twcss, type='b') #shows that 2 is the optimal amount of clusters

# k-means clustering
km9 <-kmeans(dist_eu, centers = 9) 

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston_scaled, col = km9$cluster)

To assess the optimal amount of clusters, i calculated the total within sum of squares for the k-means results from 1 to 20 clusters. The total within sum of squares is the total of all the within cluster sum of squares (WCSS), which is calculated as follows: \(WCSS=\sum_{i=1}^N (x_i=c)^2\), where \(c\) is the centroid of the \(i\)th cluster.

Plotting these, we note that four to nine clusters would suffice (annoyingly, I had forgot to put a seed so the situation looks different now). There is no clear cutoff this time, so it is highly subjective and would depend on the aims of the study and the background theory. I chose nine clusters, as after that based on the twcss x nclusters plot, it is clear that there is no gain of adding more clusters, in other words (nearly) no more of the variance of the observations is explained by additional clusters (the total distance of the observations from the centroids of the clusters is not reduced by the addition of more clusters). Also, as I had already ran the 4 clusters solution I thought this would provide an interesting comparison. Thus, I reran the k-means clustering and based on the pairwise plot we can see that the differently coloured clusters seem to be seperating the observations quite nicely.

All in all the data contains 155 observations (countries) and 8 (numeric or integer) variables as all rows with missing values have been deleted and only the following variables have been included:

  1. Sec.Edu.FMRatio = Ratio of the proportion of females (>=25 years old) with at least secondary education to that of males
  2. LabourForce.FMRatio = Ratio of the proportion of females (>=15 years old) in the labour force to that of males
  3. Eduyears.Exp = Expected years of schooling
  4. Life.Exp = Life expectancy at birth
  5. GNI = Gross National Income per capita
  6. Mat.Mort.Ratio = Maternal mortality ratio (deaths per100,000 live births)
  7. Adol.Birth.Rate = Adolescent birth rate (births per 1,000 women ages 15-19)
  8. Parl.F.Prcnt = Percentage of female representatives in the parliament

Variables

Looking at the summary statistics below we note that the variables are all on different scales, there are no missing values present and all values are positive. Based on the pairwise plot matrix of the variables (Figure 1), we can see that only the variables Eduyears.Exp and Parl.F.Prcnt seem somewhat normally distributed. The others are clearly skewed and all variabes would seem to have at least two distict categories with their own distributions as we can just about see one bigger normal distribution and one smaller for all variables. Perhaps the countries could be divided into developing and developed countries and the within group distributions would be more normal. This could be something worthwhile looking into but we will not do this now. Another important point to take note of is that not all correlations seem to be linear. For example Life expectancy and GNI would seem to have an exponential association.

Principal component analyss

Principal component analysis is a commonly used method for dimention reduction of data. All derived principal components (PC) are uncorrelated from each other and each PC captures less variance of the data than the previous PC.

Before standardization

Lets see what kind of results we get when we perform principal component analysis on our data before we standardize the variables. In general this is not a good idea as PCA is sensitive to the relative scaling of the original variables and assumes that variables with larger variance are more important than those with a smaller variance. We will do this as a exercise to see how the results change when we later perform PCA on standardized variables.

# perform principal component analysis (with the SVD method)
pca_human <- prcomp(human)
# create and print out a summary of pca_human

We end up obtaining one PC which explains pretty much all (that is, after rounding 100%) of the variance of the 8 variables in the data. Looking at the biplot we see that the variable GNI is most influencial and ends up defining PC1 while no other variable seems to matter. This variable has the gratest range and variance of all the variables. Thus it ends up getting too much weight in the analysis and the results can not be trusted as the importance of the variables using this method are not comparable without scaling. We will next redo the PCA after first scaling the variables.

Now, based on the summary of the PCA and the biplot of the first two PCs we seem to have obtained more sensible results. The first PC explains over half of the total variance of the 8 variables, and together with the second one it explains around 70%.

Interpreting the biplot obtained after tandardization

The biplot shows that the variables LabourFrce.FMRatio and Prl.F.Prcnt load on to the PC2 while all the rest contribute mainly to PC1. Therefore, PC1 would seem to depict health care and educational aspects while the second PC gender equality in the political system. Countries that fall in the top left quarter of the plot are the ones that get the desired scores on these dimensions, whereas those in the right bottom are the ones that get the scores least respected. The two PCs are uncorrelated while the variables within a PC are highly correlated (either positively or negatively).

Multiple Correspondance Analysis

Multiple Correspondance analysis is a suitable dimention reduction technique when we have categorical variables, which is the case with the tea data. Below we note that the first dimention only explains 6% of the variance in the data. When we draw the biplot, as there are so many variables and categories within the plot becomes quite messy. Once we only draw labels for the 20 categories that contribute most on the two dimensions displayed the plot becomes more readable. The categories are from multiple variables showing that not only a few variables are very important but that many variables have atleast some categories that are very influencial.

# multiple correspondence analysis
